"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"Composability is charming part of blockchain. Unlike Web 2.0, where a company might provide a product portfolio to solve a “specific problem”, Web3 tries to breakdown such “specific problem” into different \\\"Lego modules\\\".  Each modules is a protocol.\\nIn other words, in Web 2.0, if company tried to deliver complete user experience. It might not be able to rely on third parties - as any delay in any component might delay the whole project. Furthermore, integration itself might leads to leak of confidential commercial information. In this case, inbound **internal integration** is necessary.\\nHowever, if a trustless world is enabled, an “specific problem” can be resolved by integration of different protocols (Lego modules). In this case,  **external integration** is a much better choice.\\n\\nTake defi as an example, three \\\"Lego modules\\\" is necessary for the eco system:\\n\\n1. stable coin\\n2. lending\\n3. swap\\n\\nWhile certain challenges cannot be handled on chain (i.e nonce) and automation, we might introduce some bricks as a plus\\n\\n1. Oracle\\n2. Automation (Keeper)\\n\\nDifference in composability generate difference in product desgin\\n\\nIf we look into a typical perpetual futures product, it might contains:\\n\\n1. Using the **Oracle** to generate underlying assets price in Protocol\\n2. Using **Swap** (AMM) to open or close position\\n3. Users use **stable coin** to trade\\n4. Using **Automation** to liquidate position or handling margin call\\n5. LPs might stake their LP Tokens in **Lending Protocol** to get Stable Coins (i.e Dai)\\n\\nPerpetual Protocol can use such \\\"Lego Bricks\\\" to construct a product. The bricks are either developed by protocol itself(**Swap**) or 3rd party(**Automation**). Other Protocol such as Basis Trading Protocol (i.e Lemma) can use **Perpetual Protocol** as source of underlaying assets.\\n\\nComposability great facilitates liquidity on chain and create a real ecosystem, which might 